{{Infobox religious building | name = Kurumano Shrine | native_name = 久留真神社 | mapframe = yes | mapframe-zoom = 15 | mapframe-wikidata = yes | mapframe-point = none | map_type = Japan | map_caption = Kurumano Shrine | coordinates = {{coord|34.829463|136.587963}} | map_relief = 1 | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] }}
{{nihongo|'''Kurumano Shrine'''|久留真神社}} is a [[shinto shrine]] in the [[Engishiki Jinmyōchō]]. It is located in [[Ise Province]].
{{Shinto shrine | Name = Kuruma Shrine | Image = {{Image requested|cat=Suzuka City}} | Location = [[Mie Prefecture]][[Suzuka City]] Shiroko 1-15-15 | Coordinates = {{WikidataCoord|display=inline,title}} | Enshrined deity = [[Ōnamuchi no Mikoto]] | Sacred object = | Shrine rank = [[Shikinaisha]], former [[Prefectural shrine]] | Founded = | Main hall = | Other name = | Pilgrimage sites = | Annual festival = Second Saturday and Sunday of April | Rituals = | Map = {{Location map|Japan Mie|label=Kuruma Shrine|position=bottom|width=200|mark=Shinto torii icon vermillion.svg|marksize=15|float=center|caption=}} {{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=11|marker=religious-shinto|frame-align=center|frame-width=200|frame-height=200}} }} '''Kuruma Shrine''' (くるまじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in Shiroko, [[Suzuka City]], [[Mie Prefecture]]. It is listed in the [[Engishiki Jinmyōchō]] and its former shrine rank was {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q90139226|lt=Ken-sha|qq=|1=Ken-sha}}. It is also commonly known as '''Fukutoku no Miya''' (ふくとくのみや) and '''Kuruma no Megami''' (くるまのめがみ)<ref>{{Cite web|title=Prefectural Shrine Office Kuruma Shrine|url=https://jinja-net.jp/jinja-all/jsearch3all.php?jinjya=2997|access-date=2025-12-30}}</ref>.
== History == The date of its original founding is unknown. In ancient times, it is said that [[Ōkuninushi|Ōnamuchi no Mikoto]] and [[Suseri-Hime|Suserihime no Mikoto]] were enshrined in what was commonly called Ise no Mori (the present-day Shiroko area). During the reign of [[Emperor Yūryaku]], Ayanorihime no Mikoto was additionally enshrined and revered as a goddess of good fortune<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mie Prefecture Shrine Office Kuruma Shrine|url=http://kyoka.mie-jinjacho.or.jp/shrine/%e4%b9%85%e7%95%99%e7%9c%9f%e7%a5%9e%e7%a4%be/|access-date=2025-12-30}}</ref>. During the reign of [[Emperor Bidatsu]], it was divided and enshrined at {{ill|Ise-Kuruma Shrine|qid=Q128866991|lt=Ise-Kuruma Shrine|1=Ise-Kuruma Shrine}} in [[Awaji Province]]<ref>{{Cite web|title=Awajishima Tourism Association|url=https://www.awajishima-kanko.jp/manual/detail.html?bid=374|access-date=2025-12-31}}</ref>. In Kan'ei 11 (1634), it was relocated to its present location. In April 1943 (Shōwa 18), it was promoted from {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} to Prefectural shrine<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mie Prefecture Shrine Office Kuruma Shrine|url=http://kyoka.mie-jinjacho.or.jp/shrine/%e4%b9%85%e7%95%99%e7%9c%9f%e7%a5%9e%e7%a4%be/|access-date=2025-12-4}}</ref>.
== Enshrined Deities == * Main deity: Ōnamuchi no Mikoto * Associated deities: Suserihime no Mikoto, Ayanorihime no Mikoto<ref>{{Cite web|title=Prefectural Shrine Office Kuruma Shrine|url=https://jinja-net.jp/jinja-all/jsearch3all.php?jinjya=2997|access-date=2025-12-30}}</ref>
== Annual Festivals == * Second Saturday and Sunday of April * Hatsuuma Festival: First Sunday of March * Tenno Festival: Second Sunday of July * Rituals are listed in [https://dl.ndl.go.jp/pid/1257927/1/54 Special Rituals in Mie Prefecture]
